                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.415/6–2944: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Nicaragua</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Stewart</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-06-30T19:00:00-04:00"
                            >June 30, 1944—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>288. The Department feels that in view of the internal political situation in
                        Nicaragua<note n="5" xml:id="d1314fn5">Reference is to an outbreak of
                        political disturbances on June 27.</note> it would not be advisable for
                    President <pb facs="1409" n="1395" xml:id="pg_1395"/> Somoza to use the Embassy
                    balcony as a rostrum on July 4, as mentioned in your 400 of June 29, 6 p.m. You
                    should find some discreet way of bringing about the abandonment of this part of
                    his plans. The Embassy’s attitude toward the manifestation should be one of
                    cordial but circumspect cooperation.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
